# CropAbility documentation rules

## Location

| Content | Path |
|---------|------|
| Install, dependencies, runtime, CLI/API usage | **`README.md`** |
| Execution checklist | **`doc/TODO.md`** |
| Engineering progress log | **`doc/TODO_PROGRESS_LOG.md`** |
| Agent instructions | **`AGENTS.md`**, **`.cursor/rules/`** |

**`doc/`** contains only `TODO.md` and `TODO_PROGRESS_LOG.md`. Do not add other guides under `doc/`.

Do **not** create `README.md` or architecture notes under `src/test/` or `src/main/python/`.

## Language

Follow `english-only.mdc` for all doc text.

## Content alignment

When updating docs, reflect current architecture:

- Python host → Rust extension; no Java, no TorchScript, no `scripts/`.
- Single root `Cargo.toml`; tests in `src/test/python/`.
- Resources in `src/main/resources/`; models not vendored in repo.

Legacy PGL is under `archive/legacy/pgl/` — not the supported API.

## Progress logging

**When to log:** Add a new entry in `doc/TODO_PROGRESS_LOG.md` whenever you:

- Close a checklist item in `doc/TODO.md` (checkbox → `[x]`).
- Land a significant partial milestone (multi-file feature, behavior change, or blocked follow-up).
- Change repository code, tests, or validation workflow in a way future readers must reconstruct.

When closing a checkbox in `doc/TODO.md`, add a matching dated entry in `doc/TODO_PROGRESS_LOG.md` (or rely on an existing rollup entry).

**User-facing install/run changes** go in `README.md`, not new files under `doc/`.

**Be as detailed as practical.** The log is the durable engineering record for onboarding — prefer one thorough entry over several vague ones.

### Required fields (every entry)

Use the template in `doc/TODO_PROGRESS_LOG.md`. Each field must be **specific**, not placeholder text:

| Field | What to include |
|-------|-----------------|
| **Date** | ISO date (`YYYY-MM-DD`); add a second date if work spanned days. |
| **Title** | Same English title as the matching line in `doc/TODO.md` when applicable. |
| **Scope** | What problem was solved, acceptance criteria, and what was explicitly **out of scope**. |
| **Files Changed** | Concrete paths (not “various”); group by area (`src/main/rust/…`, `src/test/python/…`, `README.md`, …). |
| **Validation Steps** | Exact commands run (`pytest …`, `cargo test`, `maturin develop …`, CLI invocations) and **pass/fail** outcome. |
| **Outcome** | What now works differently; user-visible behavior; README sections updated. |
| **Risks/Follow-ups** | Open items, known gaps, or related unchecked checklist lines. |

### Strongly recommended (include when applicable)

- **Commits / PRs:** Short hash(es) or PR URL(s).
- **Design decisions:** Why this approach and alternatives rejected.
- **API / CLI surface:** New or changed public functions, PyO3 exports, subcommands, flags.
- **Test coverage:** New or updated test modules and markers (`native`, `gpu`, `slow`).
- **Checklist:** Whether `doc/TODO.md` checkbox and log entry were updated in the same change.

### Anti-patterns (do not do)

- One-line log entries without paths, commands, or outcome.
- New `doc/*.md` guides (use `README.md` or the progress log).
- Closing a checkbox without a matching log entry when repo work was done.
- Duplicating the entire diff — summarize **what** changed and **why**.
